<Text>I  went in today for a routine hygiene appointment.  My experience is another in a long list of affirming reasons why I have remained with this dental practice for over 30 years.  Brewer Family Dentistry has always taken the responsibility for the health and protection of their patients and staff very seriously.  I would not hesitate to return tomorrow if needed. They are doing an excellent job in the midst of COVID.  Read on if you are interested in more detail:
Before entering the office, hand sanitizer and masks along with a visual reminder to social distance were available.  A plexiglass barrier has been installed in the reception area, more hand sanitizer  was available in multiple locations along with more social distancing cues. Each patient received a temperature scan prior to entering the waiting area. All staff that I encountered  were wearing masks.   All non essential items have been removed from the waiting area, and remaining furniture arranged to comply with social distancing. Instead of  toys and magazines, an air filter quietly hums in the corner.   My hygienist wore a protective gown, gloves, mask and a clear shield that covered the front portion of her head and face down to her chest.  Some equipment has been either modified or upgraded to diminish aerosol disbursement.

Cons
- Very poor management team.
- They will keep your deposit no matter what and charge you even more when you move out.
- They charge you for everything, water, hot water, gas, trash, parking, and a lot of other fees so you should add at least $250 + rent.

- Cars getting broken into all the time, and security is just a joke here.

- Everything is about money here and I truly mean it.

- Clean apartments.

< review>
I had a really rough go around at Villa Torino. They did not give me any security deposit back, when I left the apartment in perfect condition and I had to leave the area due to COVID, which the management team did not care at all about.

In the time I lived there, the management team was horrible. I had a few packages I needed to pick up 30 minutes before the office closed, and one of the managers was rushing me and frustrated that I was picking my items up close to closing time, because his dog had surgery that week...

I also received calls from the management team that my rent was not paid, when it was and the payment was processing. Definitely scary to get phone calls that your rent wasn't paid for in such tough times...

It's a nice apartment complex, but not worth the trouble from the staff and the outrageous rent and lease break penalties. But I guess they're smart in that sense, they absolutely screwed me and made a ton of money off me. When I need to move back to the area, I will not choose Villa Torino and I do not recommend Villa Torino.< /review>

Been here for a year now! Love living here and the management staff are extremely polite, sweet and accomodating. The apartments are very spacious, with high ceilings, and the amount of space they provide is definitely luxury! The interior gardening and amenities are gorgeous! Everything and I mean everything fun and essential is close by, max 8 minute drive. Entertainment, lots of grocery store locations: Target, Trader Joe's, Whole Foods, Safeway, College Park Plaza,  San Pedro Square, lots of fun places to go to downtown. The place is located downtown, thus some things are to be expected while living downtown, like making sure to never leave anything in your car, and buying extra chains for your bike. Those things are unavoidable due to where the apartment is placed, and the apartment managers and the VT community do a great job communicating to each other for any suspicious activity, to minimize the problems.< /text>

<userid>109388256822342252326< /userid><username>John Chang< /username>< Time>
1560713545894</Time>
< Rate>
1< /Rate>
< Review>
First thing first: All the 5 and 4 star ratings that you see here, were sponsored by the property manager! The property incentivize residents in return for high ratings on yelp.

Pros: Close to Downtown San Jose.

Cons:
1. Majority of the tenants in this complex are students from San Jose State University. 7-8 individuals living in a single apartment.
Irrespective of time of day/night, there is always somebody on the phone in the patio or the corridor/hallways/Balconies or on the street below your apartment. Every night there is a frat party. There are Loud and obnoxious neighbor.

2. The property manager(E) and her assistant(G) are racist AF. Anytime you go to them with a complaint, they argue with you and it always end up in a verbal argument. They always retaliate with an eviction notice for minor little thing. Sooner or later you start complaining  in the fear of retaliation.

3. Poor Security: There has always been security issues at Villa Torino. The Management has failed to address these issues over the past years. Instead of improving security, the spent money on the look and feel of the community and even renovating the leasing office. The cost of adding security cameras and a DVR is much less compared to the amount they have spent on the effing planters. Every year, during the tax season the mailboxes get broken into. Apartments have been broken into in broad daylight. Residents have been attacked by homeless. Homeless have been seen wandering around in the community on several occasion. Bike and other items have been stolen from the patio/balconies of the apartments(even 3rd floor apartments!). Cars are broken into in the parking garage almost every month. The main entrances of the building are always broken and the locks don't work. There is an "off campus" security company, every time you call them, they show up more than an hour later. The tenants security is the lowest priority for EL and Gr.

4. AirBnb: At one point of time, the community had at least 3 apartments available on AirBnb. The management (Eli and Gre) were fully aware of these units, but they chose not to take any action(who knows what they got in return). There were random guests(of all kind) staying in those BnBs. The management had to shut it down after some backlash. They might have moved to VRBO or some thing else.

5. Appliances: Old and barely works. The dryers in the apartments are so old, it takes 2-3 cycles to dry your clothes. The Dish washer is a totally different beast(in a negative sense).

6. Elevators: Majority of the time the elevators in the community are broken and under repair. (Imagine carrying your Costco groceries up the stairs.)

7. Gym: Small overcrowded gym full of residents who lack basic gym etiquette.

8. Rules : The rules which are laid out by the management, change very frequently. The same set of rules don't apply to all the apartments. The management is lenient towards some apartments while the others get eviction notice.

9. Security Deposit: Needless to say, when moving out, don't have any expectation of getting any of security deposit back. They keep the security deposit in the name of "cleaning", even if they renovate the whole apartment after you move out.

Overall, these days there are a lot more options in Downtown San Jose. Pay $50-100 more, but stay away from Villa Torino and their rude Property Managers (Elis** and Greg).<//Review>

I decided to choose another location. Better than deal with this for the next 12 months.< /review>

Great wing spot. They have all you can eat wings on Monday nights. Lots of outdoor space (they even have tvs outside). Lots of beers on tap and many different wings flavors. Only wish they had more dry rub wings flavors. If you're in Ocean Beach, definitely check this place out. There's also plenty of parking available in the CVS lot directly across the street.<//Review>

<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
A small but wonderful shopping complex. The parking lot is very small, especially for the number of shops, so be prepared to park along the street. The nail salon inside, Dynasty nails, is an amazing and well priced salon with attentive and friendly staff. The Postal Annex is also very well kept with an amazing shopkeeper, and the restaurants are also very well priced for simple but well made eats. Highly recommend!</Text>

<rate>5<//rate><Text>How American is this shopping center?! Guns, Donuts, Liquor, and Buffalo wings? What?!

Yeah it's an amazing shopping center right off the freeway with almost not enough parking but close vicinity to a Jack in the Box and a gas station - so basically it's everything you could ask for in one spot. They don't call out the gun store too much because no one wants people to know where that is, but! The bar (Speakeasy) is a great place for beer and food. If you don't like their food, go to Original Buffalo wings and top it off with a donut from the donut shop.

Super place to get into trouble or take a first date!< /Text><pics>None<//pics><Response>None< /Response>< gmap_id>

< user_name>
Rose Holmes</user_name>
<time>1574097419721< /time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<text>One of my favorite places. 3.8 miles out and back. Stay left at every fork to go to the point. The first bit is paved, then you get into some dirt climbs. Be ready for dogs and dust. The creek runs in the winter. At the top intersection, continue straight across the fire road and then take the right turn past some rocks for 200+ degrees of beautiful view. On a clear calm day, you can count all the channel islands.<//text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP0sX6yY4SifjzY5_FeSRdVBjMHUhHBL_LjaU2b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOuLz5gickkGSIiDMd_FQ1QUsm8kc5NN6k4wKgs=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPX7DcSZTC2uehtQGCiF3sWfBDCoLuq6yDxi1kC=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPxArw9Xmn-soqIBNsYbBWG3mHuEH0SoepSzY5V=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><resp>None<//resp><Gmap_id>0x80e914b3c2ba19b1:0xc22fac5aa31347af<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

Easy hike, as in the first chunk of the trail is paved, and the incline up isn't too steep, it's nice and gradual. Running shoes or hiking shoes will do you just fine. Pack some sunscreen and load up on water and you'll be just fine. The view from the top is beautiful.<//text>

Inspiration point from Jesusita trail is so beautiful and relaxing. I did this out and back trail in about 1:45, not including time spent at the top. I prefer the views of the mountains to the view of the city, but the scenery on the way up is just as worth your time as any view at the top of a peak. It's beautiful and green right now (I went on 4/18/18) with little wild flowers along the trail.<//Text>

Had trouble getting a LV BumBag from the LV website this holiday. They gave inaccurate stock information saying BumBag was back ordered for weeks, way past holiday. They also stated all stores and affiliates were out. Wrong... Then as I was running out of time, I thought I would call stores directly, that customer service store put me down for a call back from the Palm Dessert store. An employee named Simon called me back and arranged for overnight delivery of the bag we needed. Not only that, but be gave me his cell number for any tracking concerns. There was a glitch with UPS so the package was delayed a couple days, but Simon made sure to follow up and the gift was sent the day before the holiday! The extra level of service that this stranger Simon provided was amazing. A real asset to LV Palm Dessert for sure! Thanks!<//Text>

< Text>
Last night (March 8) my friend and I enjoyed an absolutely delightful dinner at A16. Everything we ordered off the specials menu was fantastic. Our server, Natalia, was very charming and provided excellent recommendations of wine. All the specials were created by women chefs in honor of international women‚Äôs day. We started off with a truly remarkable chicory salad with a date vinaigrette, almonds, pickled onions and ricotta salata. Then we thoroughly enjoyed the corona bean salad with thyme vinaigrette and red onion. It is not an over statement to say these beans were life changing. Who knew a simple bean could be elevated to such a level? Props to the chef! Lastly, we shared the burrata pizza with carrot top pesto, carrot, walnuts and green garlic. They should seriously consider making those beans and the burrata pizza staples on their menu. Everyone around us was remarking on how fabulous both dishes were, we had two separate people recommend the pizza before we even sat down! I can‚Äôt wait to return and hope A16 incorporates some of these new dishes on their menu soon.<//Text>

< Text>
Had a great evening meal here. We arrived quite late and so didn't have any wait. We sat at the chef counter in the rear area of the restaurant. This spot provided us with the ideal place to watch the chefs work. It was fascinating (and we felt exhausted on their behalf!) We had been advised to order the pizza which we did. The pizza was cooked perfectly in the wood fired oven in front of our seats and the ratio of toppings was perfect (many places over-sauce etc). I'd advise to stick to wine to drink though as all of the beers were canned. The wine list is pretty good and offers bottles over a wide price range, so ordering from there is no hardship.</Text>

<username>Daniele Perretta< /username><text>I went there to try their pizza, as this place is listed as member of VPN Americas, and I expected a high quality pizza.
The place is nice, with a bar near the main entrance and a nice room for people interested in tasting food. They feature an 'open kitchen', which I like in general.
I ordered a Margherita. Pizza looked good and the tomato sauce, mozzarella and basil were fresh, but the pizza dough had a yeasty taste.
The beer I ordered was local, a good IPA, but it was canned.
Considering that the place was not busy, the service was just OK. When the pizza was ready, it stayed there, waiting to be served, for almost two minutes. It might seem nothing, but to me pizza has to be served as soon as possible (read "immediately").
Prices for the pizza and desserts are very high.
Overall, I give it a three star only because the place is nice and their menu looks great and has a lot of other choices. For such a high price I'd expect a superb pizza and an excellent service, however they were nothing exceptional. I won't go back</text></record>

Both pannini's came out cold, like they had been sitting somewhere for a while. The salad was excellent.  The bread was good but sliced too thin.  The butter was melted.  I had chicken picattta and it was not served the traditional way in pounded medallions, breaded with a light lemon/caper sauce.  It was served with fat chicked breasts and a tart sauce. <userid>107767768560438055175</userid><user_name>Samantha Berg</user_name>< date>
1434837031998</date>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< review>
Came here on a Friday group as a group of 4. We had an 8:00 reservation and we were seating immediately. The place was bigger than expected inside and it seemed fairly busy and bustling.

We started with a bottle of white wine at the recommendation of our waitress. That was where the good service ended, though. Once we asked for bread and chili oil, we started getting some serious attitude, as if those requests were incredibly demanding and outlandish. Thank goodness the food was good. The bread was fluffy but had some heavier flavors, almost like olive, to it. I couldn't get enough of it. The chili oil was perfectly spicy, more so than expected, and was perfect on the bread, pizza crust, and basically everything.

We started with the salumi, the burrata, and the summer squash salad. The salumi had three types of meat, an 'nduja served on bread, a prosciutto, and some kind of loaf style meat. The last one was my least favorite, but the other two were really good, especially the 'nduja. The burrata was perfectly creamy with sea salt on top, and I could have eaten this for days. I didn't try the bread that was served with it, as I prefer soft bread to toast, but the cheese was just awesome. The squash summer salad was light and refreshing and perfect for the sunny day we had Friday. The pecorino on top added a nice creamy factor, and the squash and other veggies were flavorful and crispy without being heavy. The olives added good substance and fat without weighing down the salad, and the mint tasted just like summer.

We ordered a bottle of red wine and two pizzas, the salsiccia and the funghi. Both were good, the funghi was better, but neither was outstanding. The spring onion on the salsiccia was overwhelming but the mushrooms on the funghi were well cooked and the flavors all went together nicely. Oddly, the pizzas were served completely uncut with a pair of scissors. While I appreciate being able to cut slices to your own size, it was messy and would have been nice to get at least a light pre-cutting.

For four of us, with tax and tip, we each paid about $55. While I enjoyed the meal, it wasn't as awesome as I wanted it to be, especially the pizzas. I'd like to come back and try some more of the small plates, but I probably won't be running back.</review>

< review>
Specializes in Southern Italian food, from the Campania/Basilicata/Puglia regions along highway A16 that connects Naples and Bari.

I've eaten here several times, and each time it's a treat: almost everything is good here, so you can't go wrong.  (I know this cuisine, since I lived in Naples for 2 years and founded a website, Wikinapoli, about food, etc. in that region).

I prefer the pizzas at Tony's in North Beach, but A16's are one of the better "Naples-style" pizzas in SF.

Tip: don't miss the chocolate budino dessert!< /review>

< review>
Stevinson Toyota East - Aurora, Colorado
After 12 years of faithful service from my Saturn, it was time to upgrade my transportation.  I had bought American cars in the past but, when I discovered that 7  local Toyota dealerships had contributed 5 million dollars to the Denver Zoo (at which I volunteer),I needed to rethink my consumer position.  I chose Stevinson Toyota East because it is one of the seven DZ contributing dealerships, it is conveniently located, and it offers hybrid vehicles with proven reliability.
It was by good luck that Jeremy Young was my salesperson. He was calm and patient as I asked many questions.   He didn't hesitate to include the general manager in our discussions about availability and pricing. I felt very confident and comfortable in making this large financial investment with this group of professionals.
Elyce Hurd introduced me to the many features of my new Prius v.  She was very professional and friendly as she set up my Bluetooth connection and walked me through some of the idiosyncrasies of my Prius v.
I would wholeheartedly recommend Stevinson Toyota East.  I would wholeheartedly recommend working with Jeremy Young.<//review>
